               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281023-240-person1263">
                  JOHN 
                  ADAMSON
               <interp inst="t18281023-240-person1263" type="surname" value="ADAMSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281023-240-person1263" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281023-240-person1263" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the son of William Adamson, a <rs id="t18281023-240-viclabel1397" type="occupation">gardener</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18281023-240-victim1262 t18281023-240-viclabel1397"></join> of <placeName id="t18281023-240-crimeloc1398">Newington</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18281023-240-crimeloc1398" type="placeName" value="Newington"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18281023-240-crimeloc1398" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18281023-240-off1395 t18281023-240-crimeloc1398"></join>. On the 20th of October, in consequence of information, I got Brown, the officer, and went to the prisoner, who was at work in our ground; we asked to see his jacket - the officer took it off the ground, and found a bundle of cauliflower-seed; he begged forgiveness, and said he would not do the like any more - it was worth about 30s.; he had 16s. a-week.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281023-240-person1264">
                  JOHN 
                  SMITH
               <interp inst="t18281023-240-person1264" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281023-240-person1264" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281023-240-person1264" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a labourer to Mr. Adamson; I saw the prisoner go into the barn where this seed is kept - I did not see him come out; he had no business there - I saw him in about ten minutes with a parcel in his hand; I gave information.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. Did you not beckon me to the barn? A. No.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281023-240-person1265">
                  JOHN 
                  MARSHALL
               <interp inst="t18281023-240-person1265" type="surname" value="MARSHALL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281023-240-person1265" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281023-240-person1265" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I saw the prisoner come out of the barn, but saw nothing in his hand; I had put this seed in a sack there.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281023-240-person1266">
                  ROBERT 
                  BROWN
               <interp inst="t18281023-240-person1266" type="surname" value="BROWN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281023-240-person1266" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281023-240-person1266" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I went up to the prisoner, and asked to see his jacket; he shewed it to me - I took it up, and this fell out of it; he begged forgive<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182810230100"></xptr>ness, and said he did not know that he had so much, or he should have put three parts of it back.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. It is done merely to throw me out of employ, as the men had whispered that I should not be there long.</p>
               <p>
